{
  "answer": "**In \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" (Chapter 11 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*), Allama Iqbal imagines a visionary journey to the Prophet Muhammad's exalted presence amid worldly turmoil.**[^1]\n\nThe poem is a dialogue in verse. Angels bring Iqbal to the Prophet, who addresses him first as the \"Nightingale of Hijaz's garden-bower,\" praising his devotion, heavenly flight, and asking what gift he brings from the world—like fragrance from a garden.[^2]\n\nIqbal's direct address to the Prophet (\"O Presence!\") follows. He laments: **\"In the world, no true repose I find; / The life for which we yearn is not for humankind. / In life's vast garden, countless flowers you can find, / But not one bud with loyalty's sweet scent entwined.\"** He then offers a \"phial of crystal bright\" containing **\"the blood of Tripoli's martyrs,\"** symbolizing the Ummah's enduring honor—something absent even from Heaven's light.[^3]\n\nThis evokes Iqbal's themes of spiritual longing, Muslim revival, and sacrifice (referencing the Italo-Turkish War's Tripoli martyrs, 1911–1912). The full poem is brief; no other direct address appears.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 11: \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" ([translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/)).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 11: \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" ([paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/#p-ae07ba)).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 11: \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" ([paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/#p-14a317)).",
